fields.description:
Attached id the maven2 project called "test-project" complete with sample pom. The test case will run in eclipse, but will fail using the plexus-compiler when executing "mvn clean test". The contents contain the example below:

public interface IEnumTest {
}

public enum EnumTest implements IEnumTest {
	ONE, TWO, THREE;
}

// failing code snippet
Class<? extends Enum<? extends IEnumTest>> enumTest = EnumTest.class;
for (Enum<? extends IEnumTest> e : enumTest.getEnumConstants()) {
	log.info("ENUM: " + e);
}


<plugin>
	<groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
	<artifactId>maven-compiler-plugin</artifactId>
	<configuration>
		<source>1.5</source>
		<target>1.5</target>
		<compilerVersion>1.5</compilerVersion>
	</configuration>
</plugin>

ERROR:

incompatible types
found   : java.lang.Enum<? extends IEnumTest>
required: java.lang.Enum<? extends IEnumTest>

Eclipse does not have an issue with compiling this, but the plexus javac compiler does!

comments.body:
What's interesting is that I found that you can get around this bug by making it stupid to the Enum's class. For Example,

for (Enum<?> e : enumTest.getEnumConstants()) {
	Enum<? extends IDTOPhase> typedEnum = e.getClass().cast(e);
}

Obviously it is silly to have to cast the same instance back on itself, but this is the only way to get around the plexus-compiler bug for "incompatible types". Again, the original code submitted works through normal javac compilation. It only has this error using the plexus-compiler.
